When you stay in Rochester's historic 19th Ward, you'll be a short walk of bike ride to Genesee Valley Park, designed by Frederick Law Olmstead and running along the Genesee River.

My house borders the University of Rochester making it convenient for visitors to U of R or to Strong or Highland hospital.

My home is close to the airport without disruptive flight noise. Many bodegas for last minute needs.

A great jumping off point for exciting venues ten minutes away in downtown Rochester.
neighborhood_overview: Historic 19th ward of Rochester is known for its many historic parks, tree lined boulevards, and proximity to restaurants, breweries, and music venues in downtown Rochester.

name: Artists’ House in Swilburg/ No Fees
description: Excellent urban location! This small house is on the edge of everything. Single-floor layout with lots of photography, art, and style. There is a movie theater, diner, Dollar Tree, gas station, and other shops within short walking distance. Frederick Douglass and Cab Calloway called this neighborhood home. Their houses are nearby.

neighborhood_overview:
The 19th Ward known as "Urban by Choice" is the neighborhood slogan for this southwest corner of the city. With 22,000 residents, the 19th Ward is the largest residential neighborhood in the city and has the oldest continuously operating neighborhood association in Rochester.

The 19th Ward holds many social events including a Square Fair in June, annual convention in November, and lively community potluck dinners. The Westside Farmer’s Market is a popular stop at St. Monica’s church. This neighborhood has its own business association and a number of block clubs.

Proximity to facilities such as Genesee Valley Park, the University of Rochester, the Erie Canal, Brooks Landing riverfront development, the Greater Rochester International Airport, and Interstate 390 makes the 19th Ward a convenient and attractive place to live.
host_about:
Welcome to our Airbnb! We're Yvonne and Earl, a proud military family with a passion for serving others. Join us in Rochester NY for a warm and joyful stay.

As parents to two amazing adult sons, we understand the significance of family and cherish the time spent with our loved ones. When we’re not hosting, we embark on travel adventures, exploring new destinations and immersing ourselves in diverse cultures and experiences.

name: Tree-View Suite + private bath. No cleaning fee
description: Make yourself at home in this private suite with tree-top views in our 120+ year-old home. Enjoy simple comfort in this 2nd-floor bedroom/living room suite. Your private bath is 3 steps away with a ceiling-to-floor curtain that adjoins it to your suite. The space has a coffee station, mini fridge w/freezer, microwv & toaster, streaming TV, work space. Lovely for a solo traveler, and couples welcome. Quick breakfast fare & snacks provided. Next to a park. Convenient to downtown AND Lake Ontario.
neighborhood_overview: We're located on a peaceful street in the Maplewood Historic District. The area has a mix of renovated and renovating houses built in the early to mid 1900s. The neighborhood is centrally located between downtown Rochester and Lake Ontario, and it hugs the Genesee River. There are several scenic parks including the Maplewood Rose Garden and Lower Falls. The Seneca Zoo & Seneca Park swan pond are just across the bridge.

name: Cozy elegance one block from Strong, near UofR/RIT
description: Kick back and relax in this calm, stylish space.  This cute little white house is one block from Strong Memorial Hospital and the Golisano Children’s Hospital.  Very close to U of R and RIT.  Once you enter you’ll immediately feel the calmness and peacefulness of the home.  Perfect for visiting professors, travel nurses and other health professionals and families visiting patients at the Strong Memorial hospital. No need to pay for hospital parking.  It’s one block to the hospital.
neighborhood_overview:
The White Coat area in Rochester likely refers to the Medical Center District, particularly around the Strong Memorial Hospital and the University of Rochester Medical Center. This region is often called the "White Coat District" due to the large number of medical professionals who work and study in the area, wearing their white lab coats.

It's a hub for medical research, healthcare, and education. You'll find top-notch hospitals, cutting-edge research facilities, and medical schools, making it a prominent center for healthcare in the region. The area typically has a mix of modern medical buildings, research facilities, and green spaces, creating a professional and academic atmosphere. CVS, Barnes and Noble are walking distance from the home. If you don’t feel like making breakfast, you can walk a block to the Mount Hope Diner. There are other nice restaurants within walking distance to the home!

neighborhood_overview:
The 19th Ward known as "Urban by Choice" is the neighborhood slogan for this southwest corner of the city. With 22,000 residents, the 19th Ward is the largest residential neighborhood in the city and has the oldest continuously operating neighborhood association in Rochester.

The 19th Ward holds many social events including a Square Fair in June, annual convention in November, and lively community potluck dinners. The Westside Farmer’s Market is a popular stop at St. Monica’s church. This neighborhood has its own business association and a number of block clubs.

Proximity to facilities such as Genesee Valley Park, the University of Rochester, the Erie Canal, Brooks Landing riverfront development, the Greater Rochester International Airport, and Interstate 390 makes the 19th Ward a convenient and attractive place to live.

Corn Hill, a historic treasure on the banks of the Genesee River next to Center City, offers the best of the old and new. It is a revitalized landmark community full of restored 19th century homes in a variety of modest and vintage styles that are blended well with 20th century townhouses and condominiums. In most cities these kinds of neighborhoods are only accessible by the wealthy but here in Rochester, people from all walks of life make Corn Hill their home

Regardless of their backgrounds, people are drawn to Corn Hill for its history, proximity (walking distance to downtown and the University of Rochester) and for its sense of community

The Corn Hill Neighbors Association is one of Rochester’s most active neighborhood associations, working hand in hand with city government and other neighborhood groups to provide for the continuing improvement of the neighborhood. neighborhood_overview:
A sprawling neighborhood immediately east of Downtown Rochester, Alexander is named for the main thoroughfare in the area lined with restaurants, bars, museums, and apartments that range from affordable to upscale. Historic East Avenue is an upscale community with several stately mansions and diverse architectural styles such as Victorian, Art Deco, Italianate, and Gothic Revival. From the Rochester Museum & Science Centre to the George Eastman Museum to Memorial Art Gallery, there’s always something to explore in this historic part of Rochester. Locals enjoy strolling along East Avenue and surrounding streets to the many British and Irish-inspired pubs that give this neighborhood a sense of nightlife just minutes from the city center.

Minutes to all the major hospitals, such as Union, Strong Memorial and Rochester General.

neighborhood_overview:
The 19th Ward known as "Urban by Choice" is the neighborhood slogan for this southwest corner of the city. With 22,000 residents, the 19th Ward is the largest residential neighborhood in the city and has the oldest continuously operating neighborhood association in Rochester.
The 19th Ward holds many social events including a Square Fair in June, annual convention in November, and lively community potluck dinners. The Westside Farmer's Market is a popular stop at St. Monica's church. This neighborhood has its own business association and a number of block clubs.
Proximity to facilities such as Genesee Valley Park, the University of Rochester, the Erie Canal, Brooks Landing riverfront development, the Greater Rochester International Airport, and Interstate 390 makes the 19th Ward a convenient and attractive place to live.
host_about: I am a travel nurse and decided to allow guests and other travel professionals stay in my home while I’m traveling! I love traveling, being outdoors, going on adventures, and spending time with family and friends. I hope you enjoy my home as much as I do!

neighborhood_overview:
The University of Rochester is located in the Neighborhood of the Arts, a vibrant and historic district known for its theaters, museums, and art galleries. The neighborhood is also home to a variety of shops, restaurants, and cafes.

The Neighborhood of the Arts is a great place to live if you're looking for a walkable and bikeable community with a lot to offer. It's also close to the university's River Campus, making it a convenient place to live for students and staff.

Here are some of the things you can do in the Neighborhood of the Arts:

Visit the Memorial Art Gallery, one of the oldest and largest art museums in New York State.
See a show at the Geva Theatre, Rochester's oldest professional theater company.
Stroll through the Rochester Public Market, a year-round farmers market with fresh produce, flowers, and crafts.
Enjoy a meal at one of the neighborhood's many restaurants, including locavore hotspots like The Red Cat and Cure.
